  "prompt": "What are shadows, midtones and highlights?",
  "response": "Shadows, midtones, and highlights are terms used in photography and image editing to describe the different levels of brightness in an image. They help photographers and editors understand and adjust the tonal range and contrast of a photo. Here's a breakdown of each term:\n\n1. **Shadows**:\n   - Shadows are the darkest parts of an image. They represent areas where the least amount of light is reaching the subject or scene.\n   - In an image, shadows can add depth and dimension, but if they are too dark, they can lose detail and become pure black.\n   - Adjusting shadows can help recover details in underexposed areas or deepen the darkness for a more dramatic effect.\n\n2. **Midtones**:\n   - Midtones are the middle range of brightness in an image, between the shadows and highlights.\n   - They are often the most prevalent tones in a photo and can significantly affect its overall look and feel.\n   - Adjusting midtones can help balance the overall exposure and bring out the details in the main subject of the image.\n\n3. **Highlights**:\n   - Highlights are the brightest parts of an image. They represent areas where the most light is hitting the subject or scene.\n   - In an image, highlights can draw attention to specific areas and add a sense of brightness and clarity.\n   - Adjusting highlights can help recover details in overexposed areas or increase the brightness for a more vibrant effect.\n\nUnderstanding and manipulating these three elements allows photographers and editors to enhance the overall quality and visual impact of their images.",
